{'s':'Chemistry','y':2020,'q':'Which of the following has the highest number of molecules? (H=1, C=12, O=16)','o':['36 g H₂O','44 g CO₂','16 g CH₄','46 g C₂H₅OH'],'ci':0,'e':'Moles: H₂O=36/18=2; CO₂=44/44=1; CH₄=16/16=1; C₂H₅OH=46/46=1. H₂O has most moles (2).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2021,'q':'The percentage by mass of nitrogen in NH₃ is: (N=14, H=1)','o':['82.35%','17.65%','50%','75%'],'ci':0,'e':'Molar mass NH₃=17. N% = (14/17)×100 = 82.35%.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2022,'q':'A 0.1 M solution of H₂SO₄ has an H⁺ ion concentration of:','o':['0.2 M','0.1 M','0.05 M','0.4 M'],'ci':0,'e':'H₂SO₄ → 2H⁺ + SO₄²⁻. [H⁺] = 2×0.1 = 0.2 M.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2023,'q':'What is the volume of 0.5 mol of O₂ at STP?','o':['11.2 L','22.4 L','44.8 L','5.6 L'],'ci':0,'e':'0.5 × 22.4 = 11.2 L.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2024,'q':'How many grams of NaCl are needed to prepare 500 mL of 0.2 M solution? (Na=23, Cl=35.5)','o':['5.85 g','11.7 g','2.925 g','58.5 g'],'ci':0,'e':'Moles = 0.2×0.5 = 0.1. Mass = 0.1×58.5 = 5.85 g.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2025,'q':'A hydrocarbon contains 85.7% C and 14.3% H. What is its empirical formula? (C=12, H=1)','o':['CH₂','CH₃','C₂H₄','C₃H₆'],'ci':0,'e':'C:85.7/12=7.14; H:14.3/1=14.3; ratio 1:2 → CH₂.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2026,'q':'The molarity of a solution containing 4.0 g of NaOH in 250 cm³ is: (Na=23, O=16, H=1)','o':['0.4 M','0.1 M','1.0 M','0.2 M'],'ci':0,'e':'Moles NaOH = 4/40=0.1. V=0.25 L. C=0.1/0.25=0.4 M.'},

// ============================================================
// SECTION 3: GAS LAWS & KINETIC THEORY (Q181–Q230)
// ============================================================
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2000,'q':'Boyle\'s law states that at constant temperature, the volume of a gas is:','o':['Inversely proportional to pressure','Directly proportional to pressure','Independent of pressure','Directly proportional to temperature'],'ci':0,'e':'Boyle: PV = k (V ∝ 1/P).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2001,'q':'Charles\'s law relates volume and:','o':['Temperature (Kelvin)','Pressure','Mass','Density'],'ci':0,'e':'Charles: V ∝ T (at constant P).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2002,'q':'The ideal gas equation is:','o':['PV = nRT','PV = NkT','Both','PV = RT'],'ci':2,'e':'PV = nRT = NkT (where N = number of molecules).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2003,'q':'A gas occupies 2 L at 1 atm. What volume does it occupy at 2 atm (constant T)?','o':['1 L','4 L','0.5 L','2 L'],'ci':0,'e':'P₁V₁ = P₂V₂ → 1×2 = 2×V₂ → V₂ = 1 L.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2004,'q':'A gas has a volume of 3 L at 300 K. What is the volume at 600 K (constant P)?','o':['6 L','1.5 L','3 L','12 L'],'ci':0,'e':'V₁/T₁ = V₂/T₂ → 3/300 = V₂/600 → V₂=6 L.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2005,'q':'The pressure exerted by a gas is due to:','o':['Collisions of molecules with the walls','Molecular weight','Gravity','Intermolecular forces'],'ci':0,'e':'Gas pressure comes from molecular impacts on container walls.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2006,'q':'At STP, 1 mole of any gas occupies:','o':['22.4 L','24.4 L','22.4 m³','24.4 m³'],'ci':0,'e':'Molar volume at STP = 22.4 L (0°C, 1 atm).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2007,'q':'Which gas deviates most from ideal behavior at high pressure?','o':['NH₃','He','H₂','N₂'],'ci':0,'e':'NH₃ has strong intermolecular forces (H‑bonding), deviates most.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2008,'q':'The kinetic theory assumes that gas molecules:','o':['Have negligible volume','Have no intermolecular forces','Move in random motion','All of these'],'ci':3,'e':'All are assumptions of the kinetic theory of ideal gases.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2009,'q':'What is the pressure of 0.5 mol of gas in a 10 L container at 300 K? (R=0.082 L·atm/mol·K)','o':['1.23 atm','2.46 atm','0.615 atm','4.92 atm'],'ci':0,'e':'P = nRT/V = (0.5×0.082×300)/10 = 1.23 atm.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2010,'q':'The root mean square speed of gas molecules is directly proportional to:','o':['√T','T','1/√T','1/T'],'ci':0,'e':'v_rms = √(3RT/M) → ∝ √T.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2011,'q':'Which of the following gases effuses the fastest?','o':['He','Ne','Ar','Kr'],'ci':0,'e':'Graham\'s law: rate ∝ 1/√M. He has the smallest molar mass.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2012,'q':'Dalton\'s law of partial pressure states that total pressure is the sum of:','o':['Partial pressures of individual gases','Volumes of individual gases','Masses of individual gases','Temperatures of individual gases'],'ci':0,'e':'Dalton: P_total = P₁ + P₂ + ...'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2013,'q':'A mixture of gases at 1 atm has partial pressures: 0.3 atm O₂ and 0.4 atm N₂. What is the partial pressure of CO₂?','o':['0.3 atm','0.1 atm','0.4 atm','0.7 atm'],'ci':0,'e':'P_total = 1 = 0.3+0.4+P_CO₂ → P_CO₂ = 0.3 atm.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2014,'q':'Which of the following is NOT a condition for ideal gas behavior?','o':['High pressure','Low pressure','High temperature','Large volume'],'ci':0,'e':'Ideal behavior is approached at low pressure and high temperature. High pressure causes deviations.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2015,'q':'Van der Waals equation corrects for:','o':['Molecular volume and intermolecular forces','Temperature and pressure','Mass and velocity','Energy and entropy'],'ci':0,'e':'The a term corrects for attraction, b term for molecular volume.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2016,'q':'A gas at 27°C has volume V. What is the volume at 127°C at constant pressure?','o':['(400/300)V','(300/400)V','2V','V/2'],'ci':0,'e':'T₁=300K, T₂=400K. V₂ = (T₂/T₁)V = (400/300)V.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2017,'q':'At constant volume, the pressure of a gas is:','o':['Directly proportional to temperature','Inversely proportional to temperature','Independent of temperature','Proportional to volume'],'ci':0,'e':'Gay‑Lussac: P ∝ T (at constant V).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2018,'q':'A gas sample has a pressure of 2 atm at 300 K. What is the pressure at 600 K if volume is constant?','o':['4 atm','2 atm','1 atm','6 atm'],'ci':0,'e':'P₁/T₁ = P₂/T₂ → 2/300 = P₂/600 → P₂ = 4 atm.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2019,'q':'The average kinetic energy of gas molecules depends on:','o':['Temperature only','Pressure only','Volume only','Molar mass'],'ci':0,'e':'KE_avg = (3/2)RT, depends only on temperature.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2020,'q':'Which of the following is a real gas that behaves ideally at low pressure?','o':['Any gas','Only noble gases','Only H₂','Only He'],'ci':0,'e':'At low pressure, all gases approach ideal behavior.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2021,'q':'The gas with the highest rate of diffusion is:','o':['H₂','O₂','CO₂','Cl₂'],'ci':0,'e':'Rate ∝ 1/√M. H₂ has smallest molar mass (2 g/mol).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2022,'q':'If the volume of a gas is halved at constant temperature, the pressure:','o':['Doubles','Halves','Quadruples','Remains same'],'ci':0,'e':'Boyle\'s law: P₁V₁ = P₂V₂ → V half → P doubles.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2023,'q':'A container holds 2 moles of N₂ and 3 moles of O₂. What is the mole fraction of N₂?','o':['0.4','0.6','0.5','0.2'],'ci':0,'e':'X_N₂ = 2/(2+3) = 0.4.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2024,'q':'The compressibility factor Z = PV/nRT. For an ideal gas, Z =:','o':['1','0','∞','>1'],'ci':0,'e':'For ideal gas, Z = 1. Deviations give Z≠1.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2025,'q':'Which gas has the highest critical temperature?','o':['H₂O','CO₂','H₂','He'],'ci':0,'e':'H₂O has strong intermolecular forces → high critical temperature.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2026,'q':'At absolute zero, the volume of an ideal gas becomes:','o':['Zero','Infinite','Constant','Negative'],'ci':0,'e':'V ∝ T; at 0 K, V = 0 (theoretical).'},

// ============================================================
// SECTION 4: ACIDS, BASES & SALTS (Q231–Q310)
// ============================================================
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2000,'q':'An acid is a substance that:','o':['Donates protons','Accepts protons','Donates electrons','Accepts electrons'],'ci':0,'e':'Bronsted‑Lowry: acid = proton donor.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2001,'q':'A base is a substance that:','o':['Accepts protons','Donates protons','Donates electrons','Accepts electrons'],'ci':0,'e':'Bronsted‑Lowry: base = proton acceptor.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2002,'q':'Which of the following is a strong acid?','o':['HCl','CH₃COOH','H₂CO₃','H₂S'],'ci':0,'e':'HCl is a strong acid (fully dissociates).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2003,'q':'Which of the following is a weak base?','o':['NH₃','NaOH','KOH','Ba(OH)₂'],'ci':0,'e':'NH₃ is a weak base (partial ionisation).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2004,'q':'The pH of a 0.01 M HCl solution is:','o':['2','1','3','4'],'ci':0,'e':'HCl is strong acid, [H⁺]=0.01 M, pH = -log(0.01)=2.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2005,'q':'What is the pH of a 0.001 M NaOH solution?','o':['11','3','12','10'],'ci':0,'e':'pOH = -log(0.001)=3; pH = 14-3=11.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2006,'q':'The salt formed from a strong acid and a weak base is:','o':['Acidic','Basic','Neutral','Amphoteric'],'ci':0,'e':'e.g., NH₄Cl (strong acid HCl + weak base NH₃) → acidic salt.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2007,'q':'Which of the following salts will produce a basic solution when dissolved in water?','o':['Na₂CO₃','NH₄Cl','NaCl','KNO₃'],'ci':0,'e':'Na₂CO₃ is salt of weak acid (H₂CO₃) and strong base (NaOH) → basic.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2008,'q':'The pH of a solution with [H⁺] = 1×10⁻⁵ M is:','o':['5','9','7','1'],'ci':0,'e':'pH = -log(1×10⁻⁵)=5.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2009,'q':'In the titration of HCl with NaOH, the equivalence point has pH:','o':['7','>7','<7','0'],'ci':0,'e':'Strong acid + strong base → neutral salt → pH = 7.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2010,'q':'Which indicator changes colour at pH 8–10?','o':['Phenolphthalein','Methyl orange','Litmus','Methyl red'],'ci':0,'e':'Phenolphthalein: colourless below 8, pink above 10.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2011,'q':'A buffer solution resists changes in:','o':['pH','Temperature','Concentration','Pressure'],'ci':0,'e':'Buffer = weak acid/base + its salt, maintains pH.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2012,'q':'Which of the following is NOT a buffer?','o':['NaCl + HCl','CH₃COOH + CH₃COONa','NH₃ + NH₄Cl','H₂CO₃ + NaHCO₃'],'ci':0,'e':'NaCl + HCl is a strong acid + salt of strong acid; not a buffer.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2013,'q':'The conjugate base of HSO₄⁻ is:','o':['SO₄²⁻','H₂SO₄','HSO₃⁻','SO₃²⁻'],'ci':0,'e':'Conjugate base = acid minus H⁺.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2014,'q':'The conjugate acid of NH₃ is:','o':['NH₄⁺','NH₂⁻','NH₂OH','N₂H₄'],'ci':0,'e':'Conjugate acid = base + H⁺.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2015,'q':'Which of the following is amphiprotic?','o':['H₂O','HCl','NaOH','NaCl'],'ci':0,'e':'H₂O can act as acid or base (donates or accepts H⁺).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2016,'q':'The salt formed when NaOH reacts with H₂SO₄ is:','o':['Na₂SO₄','NaHSO₄','Na₂SO₃','NaSO₄'],'ci':0,'e':'2NaOH + H₂SO₄ → Na₂SO₄ + 2H₂O (normal salt).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2017,'q':'A salt that contains water of crystallisation is called:','o':['Hydrated salt','Anhydrous salt','Double salt','Complex salt'],'ci':0,'e':'Hydrated salts have water molecules in their crystal structure (e.g., CuSO₄·5H₂O).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2018,'q':'Which of the following is a deliquescent substance?','o':['NaOH','NaCl','CaCO₃','SiO₂'],'ci':0,'e':'NaOH absorbs moisture from air and dissolves in it (deliquescence).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2019,'q':'Which substance is hygroscopic but not deliquescent?','o':['Concentrated H₂SO₄','NaOH','CaCl₂','MgCl₂'],'ci':0,'e':'H₂SO₄ absorbs water but does not dissolve to form a solution (does not deliquesce).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2020,'q':'The pH of a 0.1 M acetic acid (Ka=1.8×10⁻⁵) is approximately:','o':['2.87','4.76','1.0','5.0'],'ci':0,'e':'[H⁺] = √(Ka×C) = √(1.8×10⁻⁵×0.1) = 1.34×10⁻³ M; pH = -log(1.34×10⁻³) = 2.87.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2021,'q':'Which of the following is a monobasic acid?','o':['HCl','H₂SO₄','H₃PO₄','CH₃COOH'],'ci':0,'e':'Monobasic = one ionizable H⁺ (HCl).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2022,'q':'A dibasic acid has how many replaceable hydrogen atoms?','o':['2','1','3','4'],'ci':0,'e':'Dibasic = two H⁺ ions per molecule (e.g., H₂SO₄).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2023,'q':'Which of the following is a basic oxide?','o':['Na₂O','CO₂','SO₂','P₂O₅'],'ci':0,'e':'Na₂O is a basic oxide (metal oxide). Others are acidic oxides.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2024,'q':'Which of the following is an acidic oxide?','o':['CO₂','CaO','MgO','Na₂O'],'ci':0,'e':'CO₂ dissolves in water to form carbonic acid (acidic oxide).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2025,'q':'Amphoteric oxides react with both:','o':['Acids and bases','Only acids','Only bases','Salts'],'ci':0,'e':'Amphoteric oxides (e.g., Al₂O₃, ZnO) react with acids and bases.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2026,'q':'Which of the following is an example of an amphoteric oxide?','o':['Al₂O₃','Na₂O','CO₂','SO₃'],'ci':0,'e':'Al₂O₃ is amphoteric.'},

