{'s':'Chemistry','y':2000,'q':'Electrolysis is the decomposition of a compound by:','o':['Electric current','Heat','Light','Pressure'],'ci':0,'e':'Electrolysis uses electricity to drive a non‑spontaneous reaction.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2001,'q':'In electrolysis, the anode is the electrode where:','o':['Oxidation occurs','Reduction occurs','Neutralisation occurs','No reaction'],'ci':0,'e':'Anode attracts anions → oxidation (loss of electrons).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2002,'q':'The cathode is the electrode where:','o':['Reduction occurs','Oxidation occurs','Both','Neither'],'ci':0,'e':'Cathode attracts cations → reduction (gain of electrons).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2003,'q':'During electrolysis of molten NaCl, the product at the cathode is:','o':['Na','Cl₂','Na⁺','Cl⁻'],'ci':0,'e':'Na⁺ + e⁻ → Na (reduction).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2004,'q':'During electrolysis of molten NaCl, the product at the anode is:','o':['Cl₂','Na','Na⁺','Cl⁻'],'ci':0,'e':'2Cl⁻ → Cl₂ + 2e⁻ (oxidation).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2005,'q':'A faraday is equal to:','o':['96500 C','96.5 C','9.65×10⁷ C','965 C'],'ci':0,'e':'1 Faraday = charge on 1 mol of electrons = 96500 C.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2006,'q':'How many faradays are required to deposit 1 mol of Cu from Cu²⁺?','o':['2','1','3','4'],'ci':0,'e':'Cu²⁺ + 2e⁻ → Cu → 2 faradays.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2007,'q':'In the electrolysis of brine (NaCl solution), the product at the cathode is:','o':['H₂','Cl₂','Na','O₂'],'ci':0,'e':'Water is reduced preferentially: 2H₂O + 2e⁻ → H₂ + 2OH⁻.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2008,'q':'The product at the anode during electrolysis of brine (using inert electrodes) is:','o':['Cl₂','O₂','H₂','NaOH'],'ci':0,'e':'2Cl⁻ → Cl₂ + 2e⁻ (chlorine gas).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2009,'q':'Which of the following is a strong electrolyte?','o':['NaCl','CH₃COOH','NH₃','Sugar'],'ci':0,'e':'NaCl fully dissociates in water → strong electrolyte.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2010,'q':'The electrical conductivity of metals is due to:','o':['Delocalized electrons','Mobile ions','Protons','Neutrons'],'ci':0,'e':'Metals have free (delocalised) electrons that carry charge.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2011,'q':'In the electrochemical series, which metal is the strongest reducing agent?','o':['Li','K','Na','Ca'],'ci':0,'e':'Li has the most negative reduction potential → strongest reducing agent.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2012,'q':'Which of the following is displaced from its salt solution by copper?','o':['Ag','Zn','Fe','Pb'],'ci':0,'e':'Cu is less reactive than Ag, so Cu + Ag⁺ → Cu²⁺ + Ag.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2013,'q':'A galvanic cell converts:','o':['Chemical energy to electrical energy','Electrical energy to chemical energy','Heat to chemical','Light to chemical'],'ci':0,'e':'Galvanic (voltaic) cells produce electricity from spontaneous reactions.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2014,'q':'The salt bridge in a galvanic cell allows:','o':['Flow of ions to maintain charge balance','Flow of electrons','Flow of current','Flow of protons'],'ci':0,'e':'Salt bridge completes the circuit by ion migration.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2015,'q':'The standard electrode potential of hydrogen is:','o':['0.00 V','1.00 V','-0.76 V','+0.34 V'],'ci':0,'e':'Standard hydrogen electrode (SHE) is assigned 0.00 V.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2016,'q':'Which of the following ions is reduced at the cathode during electrolysis of aqueous CuSO₄?','o':['Cu²⁺','H⁺','SO₄²⁻','OH⁻'],'ci':0,'e':'Cu²⁺ has a higher reduction potential than H⁺, so Cu²⁺ is reduced first.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2017,'q':'During electrolysis of dilute H₂SO₄ with Pt electrodes, the product at the anode is:','o':['O₂','H₂','SO₃','SO₂'],'ci':0,'e':'OH⁻ → ½O₂ + H₂O + 2e⁻ (oxygen gas).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2018,'q':'The discharge potential of an ion depends on:','o':['Electrode potential and concentration','Only concentration','Only temperature','Only pressure'],'ci':0,'e':'Discharge depends on standard potential and ion concentration (Nernst equation).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2019,'q':'Which of the following will not undergo electrolysis?','o':['Solid NaCl','Molten NaCl','Aqueous NaCl','All can electrolyse'],'ci':0,'e':'Solid NaCl has no free ions; electrolysis requires mobile ions.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2020,'q':'In the electrolysis of aqueous NaCl, what is formed at the cathode?','o':['H₂','Na','Cl₂','O₂'],'ci':0,'e':'Water is reduced to H₂ (since Na⁺ is not easily reduced in water).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2021,'q':'The anode in an electrochemical cell is:','o':['Negative electrode in a galvanic cell, positive in electrolytic cell','Positive in both','Negative in both','Positive in galvanic, negative in electrolytic'],'ci':0,'e':'Anode = negative in galvanic (oxidation), positive in electrolytic (oxidation).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2022,'q':'A metal that is electroplated uses:','o':['Electrolysis','Galvanic cell','Neutralisation','Combustion'],'ci':0,'e':'Electroplating is done using electrolysis (deposition of metal ions).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2023,'q':'The number of moles of electrons required to deposit 1 mol of Al from Al³⁺ is:','o':['3','1','2','4'],'ci':0,'e':'Al³⁺ + 3e⁻ → Al → 3 faradays.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2024,'q':'In the electrolysis of CuSO₄ with copper electrodes, the mass of the anode:','o':['Decreases','Increases','Remains same','Dissolves completely'],'ci':0,'e':'Copper from anode dissolves as Cu²⁺ (anode loses mass).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2025,'q':'In the electrolysis of CuSO₄ with inert electrodes, the solution becomes:','o':['More acidic','More basic','Neutral','Unchanged'],'ci':0,'e':'2H₂O → O₂ + 4H⁺ + 4e⁻ at anode; H⁺ increases → acidic.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2026,'q':'The Faraday constant is the charge on:','o':['1 mole of electrons','1 mole of protons','1 mole of ions','1 gram of electrons'],'ci':0,'e':'1 F = charge on 1 mole of e⁻ = 96500 C.'},

