// SECTION 6: THERMODYNAMICS & KINETICS (Q381–Q430)
// ============================================================
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2000,'q':'Exothermic reactions:','o':['Release heat','Absorb heat','Require catalyst','Are spontaneous always'],'ci':0,'e':'Exothermic = ΔH negative (heat released).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2001,'q':'Endothermic reactions:','o':['Absorb heat','Release heat','Have negative ΔH','Produce light'],'ci':0,'e':'Endothermic = ΔH positive (heat absorbed).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2002,'q':'The enthalpy change of a reaction depends on:','o':['Initial and final states','Pathway','Rate','Catalyst'],'ci':0,'e':'Enthalpy is a state function; ΔH depends only on initial and final states.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2003,'q':'The activation energy is the minimum energy required for:','o':['A reaction to occur','A bond to break','A catalyst to work','A gas to expand'],'ci':0,'e':'Activation energy is the energy barrier that reactants must overcome.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2004,'q':'A catalyst:','o':['Lowers activation energy','Increases activation energy','Changes ΔH','Is consumed in reaction'],'ci':0,'e':'Catalysts provide an alternative pathway with lower Ea.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2005,'q':'The rate of a reaction increases with temperature because:','o':['More molecules have energy > Ea','Molecules collide less','Concentration changes','Pressure decreases'],'ci':0,'e':'Higher T increases the fraction of molecules with sufficient energy.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2006,'q':'The law of mass action states that the rate is proportional to:','o':['Product of concentrations of reactants','Product of concentrations of products','Sum of concentrations','Square of concentrations'],'ci':0,'e':'Rate ∝ [A]^a[B]^b for elementary reactions.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2007,'q':'The order of a reaction is determined by:','o':['Experiment','Stoichiometry','Temperature','Pressure'],'ci':0,'e':'Reaction order is empirical, determined from experimental data.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2008,'q':'A zero‑order reaction has a rate that:','o':['Is independent of concentration','Doubles when concentration doubles','Is proportional to concentration','Is proportional to square of concentration'],'ci':0,'e':'Rate = k (independent of [reactant]).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2009,'q':'The half‑life of a first‑order reaction:','o':['Is independent of initial concentration','Depends on initial concentration','Is inversely proportional to initial concentration','Is directly proportional to initial concentration'],'ci':0,'e':'t₁/₂ = 0.693/k (constant for first‑order).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2010,'q':'Which of the following increases the rate of a reaction?','o':['Increasing temperature','Adding catalyst','Increasing concentration','All of these'],'ci':3,'e':'All increase reaction rate (except in some specific cases).'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2011,'q':'The collision theory states that for a reaction to occur, molecules must:','o':['Collide with sufficient energy and correct orientation','Collide with any energy','Be in same phase','Have similar masses'],'ci':0,'e':'Effective collisions require energy ≥ Ea and proper geometry.'},
{'s':'Chemistry','y':2012,'q':'In a reversible reaction at equilibrium, the rate of forward reaction equals:','o':['Rate of reverse reaction','Zero','Maximum','Infinity'],'ci':0,'e':'Equilibrium = dynamic balance of forward and reverse rates.'},
